segments.text: Yeah, well, we're at Guam.
All right.
My citation speaks for itself.
Yeah, I would.
I already read my citation.
The people I prosecuted
There was a guy that came up there to Guam, had three stripes on him, and they charged him with selling whiskey at $50 or $75 a bottle.
I locked the son of a bitch up just like that.
He said, you can't lock me up.
I said, no.
He said, I'm an officer.
They want to lock you up.
Well, I'll teach you how to sell whiskey around these islands for $75 a quart.
They locked that son of a bitch up right there on Guam.
Then sent some more of the same thing.
What happened to them?
Then they finally got the WSA Admiral Lambs.
Admiral Lambs was head of the War Shipping Administration.
Then through him, they come down and got him out and put him off the island.
Was he prosecuted?
Huh?
Was he a prosecutor?
Well, I didn't have anything to do with the courts on Guam.
Oh, okay, okay.
Well, I locked the bastards up and put them in the stockade.
But he wasn't going to be put in that stockade.
I didn't have any goddamn places to put people, you know.
Put them where I could put them, that's all.
I was a little bit acid, I'll admit, but you know what I mean.
I was taught that way by my commanding general.
You know?
Mm-hmm.
Will you tell me how you got the Legion of Merit?
I'm going to tell you in a minute.
The Bronze Star?
I'm trying to find it now.
Okay.
I'm going to take it.
Because I'd like to find out why you got the Bronze Star in the Legion of Merit.
All right.
That's on.

In the name of the President of the United States, Commander Marianas, the United States Pacific Fleet takes pledge in presenting the Legion of Merit to Colonel Victor A. Baraka of the United States Marine Corps for service that is set forth in the following.
For meritorious conduct,

in the performance of outstanding service as commanding officer of the 1st Base Headquarters Battalion, Fleet Marine Force Pacific and Headquarters Commandant of Island Command Guam from the 2nd of May 1944 to the 17th of January 1945 to September 1946.
He rendered valuable service in connection with the early stages of planning for the coming Guam operation and the setting up of the Island Command on the island as commanding officer of the 1st
Base Headquarters Battalion and Headquarters Commandant.

During the early trying days of the occupation, his tireless efforts, initiatives, sound judgment, and able administrative ability were major factors which contributed materially to the early successful function of the Island Command.
He ran an outstanding service in advising the island commander in connection with the formulation of policy, initiation of measures for the proper police of the island.
He built up a police organization that was modeled in efficiency.

As Pro-Marshal Guam, one of the major advance bases in the Pacific, with jurisdiction over the vast numbers of troops of all armed service of the United States, he was assigned a task of great responsibility demanding unusual ability.
which he successfully carried out in an exemplary manner.
His unwavering devotion to duty and conduct through and keeping with the highest tradition of the United States Naval Service.
Signed, Admiral Murray.
Now, why'd you get the brown star?
All right, well, I'll give you this one of these.
I think I have two.
Oh, good.
I believe I got... Well, you're kidding me.
All right, so I traded for the brown star.
These are all letters of congratulations they sent along with you.
And you got this from the 20th Air Force, the Bronze Star from the 20th Air Force.
In the Army.
And the U.S. Army.
Citation of the Bronze Star Medal.

Colonel Victor Abraham, United States Marine Corps Reserve, for meritorious achievement in connection with the military operation against the enemy on Guam from July the 17th to the 2nd of September, 1945.

As Provo Marshal of Guam, Colonel Baraka displayed outstanding professional competence and resources in the, and ably coordinating military, ably coordinating military policies duties of the Army, Navy, and Marine organizations throughout
throughout Guam.

He exhibited superior ability in establishing and directing procedures, providing for traffic and highway control, and for the security and protection of ammunition, explosives, and inflammable material in storage and in transit.

During the crucial period of the combat preparation, his exceptional skill and organization ability were conspicuous evidence in the able manner in which he expedited the movement of troops, supplies, and ammunition with the utmost safety and dispatch.
over rules which were in process of construction, thereby contributing greatly to the commencement of operations against the enemy on schedule.
Through his deceitful judgment, foresight, and unremitting devotion to duty, Colonel Baraka made a notable contribution to support the combat operations.
And when did you leave?
as Provost Marshal of Guam and go to this brief duty of China, but you don't tell us anything.
Well, I know that was just while I was still on duty in Guam, I was still assigned.
Well, why'd they send you to China?
Well, they sent me up there on a trip to, first to observe the
They served Kinsen, Pekin, Tsing Wan Tao, and Shanghai, where we Marines had all served and were still there.
Uh-huh.
And what kind ofwere you supposed to make a report?
I didn't make any report at all.
Well, whyto observe them?
Well, why did they Observe them?
They wanted me to have that experience.
That was all.
Oh, I see.
I had nothing to do after that.
What did you think about it?
What did you think about China?
Great country.
Great country.
It's a shame the Communists were running.
What did you think about the Chinese people that you met?
I liked them.
I liked them.
He wanted to copy this one.
I don't know.
I don't see...
I better check in on that blonde star business someplace I don't know where they are.
Citation for it.
I got the damn thing.
Well, you just read it.
The bronze star citation.
You just read it.
Right here.
You just read that.
I don't... And did you leave Guam then in January of 1946 to become the island commander?
No, no.
This is all under the island commander.
Okay, okay.
I'm trying to find my damn citation.
This one or you're just kidding?
I wish to express my gratification upon the recognition of your meritorious achievement in connection with the military operation against the enemy on Guam, 17th of January to 2nd of September, 1945.
It is evident by the award you have received a Bronze Star with citations
by the commanding general, United States Army Forces Pacific, and by direction of the President of the United States.
That's what you got into the record.
That's who gave it to me.
And who signed that?
Huh?
Who sent that letter to you?
Vandegrift.
So he must have had the stuff in front of him someplace.
I don't have, I have only the citation, but I don't, but he tells me who it's signed by.
That's all I want to know.
Did I give you one of those?
Yeah, right, yeah.
What have you got, the Legion of Merit?
Yeah, I have it.
But you don't have a bronze star.
Well, you only have one copy, so maybe you should keep it.
Well, you got it in the record, didn't you?
Yeah, well, you just read it to the record.
Okay.
Let's see here.
So that takes care of that.
Well... And then let's continue on this.
About Guam.
When did you leave Guam?
Wait a minute.
What is the... What is the, uh, the, uh...
What is the Legion of Merit?
What does it say?
From what dates to what dates?
2 September 1945.
Alright, well I left there in 1940.
What time is it?
September?
Yeah.
But you see here on this other...
That'd be 46 then.
Okay, so you left in 1946.
Come along in there.
Okay, and then you returned directly to Camp Pendleton?
Camp Pendleton.
After you left Guam?
That's right.
And then at Camp Pendleton, then I took a leave and I had to come back there because they were talking about trying to get me to
to stay on active duty.
You were a full colonel now.
Yeah.
But the way everything went out, I'm glad it didn't because I would have had to sacrifice too much here and reestablish myself.
In Houston?
Yeah.
Because I had property and stuff here and I had a wife here.
So you decided in 1946 that you They decided.
Hell, I'd have stayed as a damn fool.
I'd have stayed on, I guess, and took the whipping, I guess.
But I'm glad it worked out that way.
But the Marines then decided that it was time for your retirement?
No, it was time to go back to inactive duty.
To go to inactive duty.
But you wanted to stay on active duty.
I'd have sooner stayed, yeah.
But anyhow, because...
But I had property back here, and it would be a sacrifice if I did.
But anyhow, I couldn't stay on for just a few more years.
I'd have to retire anyhow, you see.
So what was the point?
You know, it wasn't at my age.
Okay.
So you went back to reserve duty at Corpus Christi Naval Air Station?
All right.
Well, that's where that was my last station.
Okay.
I had to go there.
Okay.
So tell me about that.
Well, that's just there, and you... What were you in charge of?
Huh?
Nothing.
Nothing.
I was just in transit.
Oh, okay, in transit.
So you were a colonel in transit.
I got to see my good buddies that was there.
Sure.
So you went from Camp Pendleton to Corvus Christi Naval Air Station, and then back to...
You were a lead from active duty in 1947?
47, I forget what time.
All right, and organized a volunteer training unit in Houston.
Okay, at this time you were still a colonel.
That's right.
And you graduated in the industrial mobilization course.
I took that.
What was the industrial mobilization course?
It's all about stocking up material for war.
There's a diploma sitting over there.
You can look at that thing.
Okay.
And then you served on Policy Board 8 Marine Corps District.
That's right, in New Orleans.
Okay, and?
In the Promotion Board at Headquarters Marine Corps.
Okay.
But tell me about these reserve duties.
Well, they got full pay and everything.
Were you in charge?
Well, I was always a senior, you know.
The volunteer training unit, my God, man, I had 200 and something Marine Reserve officers, so I had to get rid of the aviators and set them off for themselves.
And what did I say I was looking for?
Well, we were talking about the industrial mobilization course, and you got up and started looking for something.
I said I had a diploma here at some place.
I was wondering what you did on the 8th Corps, on the policy board.
Well, on the policy board, you set the policy for the whole district.
Okay, and how large is that district?
Oh, hell, it run into Oklahoma, Arizona at that time.
Southern Reserve District, the Reserve District.
See, we had troops in all these places.
By that time, you had organized reserves, battalions, all these places.
That's what that policy board was about.
Okay, and you set the policy, but you weren't the senior officer.
Yes, I was.
Oh, you were the senior officer.
And the guy, you know what Tabasco Sauce is?
So you were the director, you were the CO. Tabasco Sauce is, Tabasco Sauce, McElhinney,
McElhinney was one of the finest combat battalion Marine Corps ever had in history.
And he's the guy that runs that Spice Island down there, Tabasco South.
And he's a big, he retired him as a brigadier without pay because he didn't have enough time in.
But he's a guy that's a big beneficiary of the Marine Military Academy down here that somebody better take cognizance of.
He's doing a good job.
Oh, great.
All right, down there we are.
Well, what kind of policies did you come up with?
Were you the CO of that then?
No, I was a senior member.
They put certain propositions in front of you, and we had to discuss them and pass on them.
Okay.
The whole district.
Were there any that you thought were really important that should be on tape?
No.
I think that everything they were doing was according to training.
The troops were being trained properly, the armors were being constructed, the units were being organized, and the people were attending the business.
And then you had two tours of duty at headquarters U.S. Marine Corps Promotion Board.
Yeah, I've got pictures of that.
So you were in charge.
Where is that?
At Washington, D.C.
Okay, and you were in charge.
No, I wasn't in charge.
I was just a member of the board.
Right, you were a member of the board, and you were reviewing people's service records to make recommendations?
Promotion.
Okay.
pictures of them over there somewhere.
And would you go, how long were you there?
Well, each tour lasted two weeks.
Okay.
And you'd do this every year, once every two?
I did two tours.
Okay, okay.
So that's the way that you'd fill your active reserve by going to that?
Sure, that's right.
Okay.
And then you remained active in various assignments, for example, until 1955 when you retired.
That's right.
But what were some of those assignments?
Well, uh, the, uh, this volunteer training unit took a couple hours commanding off of that until practically retired.
Mm-hmm.
Mm-hmm.
Okay.
And we met every week.
Okay.
How'd you make general?
I told you on that combat citation.
Mm-hmm.
On retirement, under the law.
Okay.
They had to promote me.
And I read your citations.
Yeah, I know.
I participated in visitation rites of the Vietnam veterans.
I got pictures there where I went down to Corpus Christi two or three times and decorated those people and all that stuff.
Pictures of all that.
And I said, I'm a member of the military affairs committee of the chamber of all veterans, all grades in the American Marine Corps Reserve.
There's my chapter window.
You can pull that right down there, take them pictures off of there.
Right here.
Oh, no, no, over there.
Underneath there, you can see.
Yeah, I saw that.
All right, okay.
My chapter won that twice.
Mm-hmm.
They have a chapter named after me.
Yeah, I know that.
How did that come about?
How did it come about that they named a reserve corps chapter after you?
Because the other chapter was named after
The other one was named after John W. Thompson?
No, the chapter was named that.
See?
And they decided, well, they'd honored him long enough so they wanted to honor me, so they named it.
And these were your men who named it for you?
No, Marine officers.
But these are formerly your subordinates?
Some of these men have been your subordinates?
Not enlisted men.
Some of them officers have been my subordinates.
I see.
Uh-huh.
Did you want to retire from the Marine Corps in 55 or would you rather have stayed?
By age, I had to under the law.
Yeah.
Okay.
I got various letters appreciating every place I served.
In fact, those natives in Samoa
They come up.
My deputy came to me and he said, they're meeting over there.
They want you.
I said, what do they want me about?
He said, they want to talk to you.
The high chief got up and he said, you have shown us the light.
You've shown us how to work.
You've shown us how to appreciate America.
We want you to extend your duty as a lawyer, seeley, seeley.
That means high lawyer.
So I had to tell them, no, I want the orders right now.
If the war is going the other way, I don't want to stay there.
And I went on, you see.
Well, that was nice of them to say.
Sure it was.
Oh, yeah, they all respected me.
I had no trouble.
When they found out that I didn't know bullshit, that I wasn't going to trade pussy for, you know, for favor.
Is that on the record?
Yeah, now I'm turning it back on.
Oh, wait, we're going to...
We're not done yet, are we?
Can I ask you some more questions?
Yeah.
Okay, so I wanted to ask you, how did you feel on the day of your retirement?
Do you remember?
Did you feel pretty sad about it?
Well, not exactly.
I did in a way, yes, but...
You know, those times I had to come to everybody.
And of course, I got pictures there with the military, the Chamber of Commerce, the Honored Men and so forth and so on and all that.
So, you know, I'm proud to be a Marine.
I went to the convention in New Orleans the end of May.
I'm the oldest guy there all the time, but I promised John Smith I'd always be there.
I'm Mads Smith, you know, heard of him maybe.
So that's that.

Well can we talk, I'd just like to talk about A&M just a little bit here, and you know some people say that A&M is more than just a college or a university, that it's something, it's more than just that.
Do you agree, and if it is, what do you think it is?
It's a fraternity.
It's a way of life.
It's a way of life.
It's a religion, just like being a Marine.
It's a satisfaction within one to know he's an Aggie and he's accomplished something.
And not only him has he accomplished, but others have in every walk of life.
And that's why I say it's a fraternity, though.
Okay, well, what ways do you think that A&M changed your life?
I don't know if A&M changed my life.
A&M molded my life.
It didn't change my life.
Moved it?
Molded it.
Molded it.
Okay, well, how did it mold it then?
Well, I'm not unhappy with the happenings in my life.
No, I mean...
I don't understand.
Would you explain what you mean by molded?
Well, molding my life means that I can look around at a fellow Aggies, and I'm proud of them.
They're proud of me.
But I have given, too.
I've been a member of the Ex-Student Association, on the board of directors of the Ex-Student Association.
I've been president of the Houston A&M Club.
I've given, and I've been interested in young people.
I've been on recruiting tours for the Marine Corps, I mean for the
With athletics, I've been on recruiting for scholars.
And I get up all my, I go down to that A&M club every Monday that I can.
I do all I can do.
Okay.
Do you think that, I want to ask you as a general, how does somebody who's been a success in the military,
Do you think that you've become a success in the military the same way you do as a lawyer or any other professional field?
No, because everybody will have the opportunity to show what they can do.
I was lucky that a general had faith in me and knew what I could do.
That's when it took away from one staff to another.
Generals would fight for my service.
I'm not being braggadocious about it.
Because they knew I'd work.
I was stupid enough to work.
There was no politics to me.
I just called it like it is.
That's it.
Would you have considered yourself ambitious?
Perhaps if I were more ambitious, maybe I'd have acquired more.
I've been a million-dollar bracket once.
I don't mean to be braggadocious about it, but I'm glad I'm not in that anymore.
But when you were in the military, did you ever, was there a time when you thought that you might want to be a general or did you just sort of leave your advancement to, well, your superiors?
No, I never, I never thought.
The only thing I ever wanted out of the Marine Corps was to be qualified to be the globe eagle and anchor.
That was my only thought of affiliation with the service because I was proud to be a Marine.
What do you think, in your whole military career as a Marine, what do you think, when you look back on it, what do you think were the best accomplishments?
Because you've had a really rich career out of Guam and Samoa and things like that.
What did you think was the best thing, your best accomplishment?
I think they were both good.
And I think if I had made a reputation back in Samoa, I wouldn't have mounted anything up in...
In Guam, because that was a big, big job.
That was bigger than that native job down there because I was head of these things and I could almost do all that.
But this thing here was nuts.
I had to deal with all military personnel here, Japanese prisoners and things like that.
This way I had military personnel also to back me up and back me up in my civilian, whatever it is.

Was there anything in your military career that you thought, well, maybe I could have done a better job on that, or maybe I just sort of, I mean, I just, I wish, when you think back, you said, well, that you might say, well, I wish, you know, that was sort of a shortcoming on my part.
Maybe I could have done more there.
Was there anything like that?
Never.
You always felt that you were giving 100%?
I always felt that I was giving everything that was required of me.
Okay, okay.
You know, a lot of,
young core kids today talk about leadership and in order to become a general you have to have some kind of a leadership potential.
You've got to deliver your job that they give you.
You've got to be able to subordinate.
I mean, delegate.
Supervise.
Subordinate.
Be patient.
Psychoanalyze people.
Put yourself in their shoes.
What would you do?
Okay, so I want to know how you define leadership, in other words.
You're obviously a general and a leader, so if you had to go to Aggieland and give a talk to a bunch of corpsmen on leadership, how would you define it?
What would you tell them?
Well, the quality of leadership is having first integrity.
Mm-hmm, mm-hmm.
And having confidence in what you're talking about and knowing your subject, know what you're talking about.
Mm-hmm.

And remember, I was scared to death when I was in front of a platoon as a second lieutenant because I was afraid somebody in that platoon was a graduate of the University of Minnesota with magna cum laude and knew more than I did.
So therefore, I was scared of my subject.
I had to be, in my own mind, I had to prepare myself to do what I was supposed to do.
So preparation comes in all that.
And everything.
It's just not just happens.
And determination.
Okay.
And I gave you all that there with the Marines.
I gave you that thing right over there, resources, all that kind of business.
The Marines got to learn how to shoot.
Something like that.
Yeah, I see that.
I have this thing right here.
Which he wrote.
You can send it back to me.
There it is.
Patriotism and loyal, discipline, self-respect and pride, alertness, spiritual cheerfulness, enthusiasm, initiative, resourcefulness.
You can't use that typewriter.
You can use a pen.
Aggressiveness, determination and tenacity.
Stick to a thing.
The best shot in the world, of course.
Privilege and honor of being a Marine.
But these other things in the middle there are things that bring all this thing up.
a clean mind, a clean body, and deliver the message to Garcia.
You ever heard of that before?
During the Spanish-American War, they gave this ensign this job to deliver this message, and he killed people, but he delivered the message to Garcia.
Get the job done.
These are all the things in here to bring me to shift.
Okay, did you have all these values?
Well, now that we have it on tape, you can keep it.
Did we have all these... Did you, as a leader, did you have all those values, do you think?
I think I tried to.
Okay, okay.
I aspired to them.
Ain't nobody perfect.
Right, right, right.
See?
So...
There you are.
The only thing is that...
I say the only thing...
Maybe some other time we'll get all these pictures together for you.
Okay.
You know, there's different types of leaders, General.
I know that.
There are leaders who think that go out using a lot of obscenity, we'll put it around you.
That only makes the troops know you don't know what the hell you're doing.
You're showing off.
Well, what about, you know,
In the military, there's sort of the General Patton type, who's a tough guy, and there's sort of...
I believe in him.
And there's sort of the Eisenhower type, who's more of one who works for cooperation.
What kind of leader were you, and which one did you like the most?
I liked Patton.
Because he believed in training.
Okay.
And he believed also...
If something's got to be done, you got to do it, whether you like it or not.
Then on top of that, I looked at the background of Patton.
Patton said... You can have that.
And here is some more.
I will give you that some other time.
When was this given to General Larson?
During the time when it passed to me.
You can have it.
I've got plenty of them.
So this is like 1945?
Yeah.
You've got to have confidence.
Did you know that I shouldn't tell you this, but there's one guy that said I could have been president of A&M College.
You know who that was?
Caesar Augusta Hone, the guy who wrote The Dutchman on the Brazzers.
You ever read it?
No, I haven't read it, but I've heard of it, yeah.
That's how much he thought of me.
I lived in a tent right in front of his where he had his candy shop in his trunk.
He and old Dixon.
Did you want it?
Who?
I never thought, my god, I never thought I'd be capable of being president of the A&M College.
But Judge Holman thought it after I got to be a lawyer.
I wasn't no great John Marshall or anything like that.
I guess, you know, I took, I took the, I took the law as something that I needed to help hold on what I could get, the holding life perhaps, you know.
I never aspired to be a big corporation lawyer or anything like this, nothing like that.
But I helped a lot of people acquire homes, because we represented the mortgage loan people.
And I got a lot of contractors mad at me, too, because when they'd come up there and say they were going to do something for so much money, I knew damn well they couldn't do it.
And then in the end, you wind up with a lien, and a this, and a that, and the other, and a lawsuit.
The best way to have a lawsuit is compromise.
Don't have any lawsuits.
That's why I want to tell you this.
My brother blew his brains out on it.
He wouldn't listen to what I was talking about.
We owned props from Woodhead to Hazard, North Boulevard, Bissonette, and South Boulevard, and he wouldn't listen to them.
And all he had to do was compromise and give the Salmon Hospital estate $2,500 for 50 by 200 feet on Hazard Street and it would have been all over.
But in the end, no, he wouldn't do it.
He said I didn't know what I was talking about.
He's 18 years older than I am.
There's a picture over there and he finally in the end we lost and he blew his brains out.
So you see I've had all I've had so much.
Anyhow I don't know I don't want to wear you out.
I don't want to wear you out.
Well I wanted to ask you just one more thing.
All right.
And that deals with
It deals with the changes that have taken place at A&M over the last, well, since General Rudder, okay?
And I wanted, I'm sure that you know General Rudder, our new General Rudder, and what do you think of those changes?
You know, A&M no longer has mandatory corps, and now it has women, and now it has blacks, and it's gone from 6,000 to 34,000.
What do you think of all those changes?
Well, the first thing I think that the,
About the Corps, I want to get in on that.
I think that they've bastardized the Smith-Lever Act, the Howell Act, the Marl Act, because it said they should teach military science and tactics.
That's why you got a land grant.
I understand that we couldn't put people back in the Corps after World War I, World War II, Korea, and Vietnam when they'd already had the service.
Mm-hmm.
But you still had to obligate them to military science and tactics and training for at least two years.
And they should have held to that, regardless.
Regardless.
Now, I know why.
Mothers commenced losing their sons in the this and the that and the other.
And if they didn't get the girls in there, they wasn't going to have their appropriations.
If they didn't put the blacks in there, you'd be violating the Civil Rights Act.
So history changes everything.
So did you think it was a good idea to have the women and the blacks?
What do you think?
What's your opinion?
You couldn't stop that.
You couldn't stop the black part of it.
The women part, you couldn't stop that either because of the changing times.
Okay.
Changing times.
Not like old Mr. Smith said, the great benefactor who gives this Aggie...
the Solar Rolls reunion last night, he's got it perpetuated, financed forever.
He hadn't got, he said all A&M needed was a football team, a band, and a cadet corps.
But he had to give up with the women part and all that.
I still believe that, but I know that the school game couldn't grow.
And so you thought that growth was good for it?
I don't think, I think it's something that had to be.
Oh, okay.
It had to be, it had to come to pass.
On a changing time, women's rights, and all of that.
And on top of that, showing the grades that these women make, some of these women make better grades than men.
And on top of that, on some of the jobs they're getting, which I hear at the A&M Club, industrial work, and this, that, and the other.
But the only thing I have got to gripe at A&M College is about one thing, that every male should have two years of military training.
That's it.
That's the only gripe I have.
I don't say about the women.
I've got a gripe on that.
I say they're bastardizing the Smith-Cleaver Act.
And I know why they're doing it, on politics.
A lot of times people don't want to send a kid to A&M.
They're probably going to send him to war and get him killed.
Well, everybody owes the obligation.
I made a speech.

I made a speech at the Chamber of Commerce on the Marine Corps birthday several years ago in Pasadena.
